
Topic: Nn:

Nn: Change the current default network
    drive.

Usage:

N<n>:

where 'n' is required and denotes a
device number 1-8.

After changing the default network
drive, the command prompt is updated
reflect the new default network drive.

Note: No check is made regarding the
status of the mount point for the new
default network drive. That is, it is
possible to switch to a network drive
that has no assigned mount point.

The N: device will also respond to
calls from software to the D: device.
This allows software created with the
expectation of transferring data with
floppy disks to work with NOS.
Example:

N2:

